from langchain_openai import ChatOpenAI
from dotenv import load_dotenv
from langchain_core.prompts import PromptTemplate
from langchain_core.output_parsers import StrOutputParser
from langchain_core.runnables import RunnableParallel
from langchain_core.output_parsers import StrOutputParser

load_dotenv()

model = ChatOpenAI()

prompt1=PromptTemplate(
    template='Generate a detailed notes on below \n {text1}',
    input_variables=['text1']
)


prompt2=PromptTemplate(
    template='Generate a detailed notes on below \n {text2}',
    input_variables=['text2']
)


prompt3 = PromptTemplate(
    template="""
Below are two generated notes.

Notes 1:
{note1}

Notes 2:
{note2}

Merge both notes and create 10 multiple-choice questions with answers.
""",
    input_variables=['note1', 'note2']
)


parser = StrOutputParser()
parallel_chain= RunnableParallel({
    'note1':prompt1 |model | parser ,
    'note2': prompt2 | model | parser
}
)

merger_chain = prompt3 |model | parser
chain  = parallel_chain | merger_chain

aws_s3="""
Amazon S3, also known as Amazon Simple Storage Service, is one of the most popular cloud storage services provided by Amazon Web Services and is designed to store and retrieve any amount of data from anywhere over the internet with high scalability, durability, availability, and security. Amazon S3 is an object storage service where data is stored as objects inside logical containers called buckets. Each object in S3 consists of the actual file data, metadata, and a unique identifier known as the object key. S3 is widely used by startups, enterprises, developers, and government organizations for storing application data, backups, archives, logs, media files, big data datasets, machine learning data, and static website content. One of the major advantages of S3 is its extremely high durability, which is designed for 99.999999999% durability, commonly referred to as eleven nines. This durability is achieved through automatic replication of data across multiple devices and facilities within an AWS Region. Amazon S3 is highly scalable and can handle virtually unlimited storage capacity without users needing to manage infrastructure or provisioning manually. S3 supports multiple storage classes optimized for different access patterns and cost requirements, including S3 Standard, S3 Intelligent-Tiering, S3 Standard-IA, S3 One Zone-IA, S3 Glacier Instant Retrieval, S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval, and S3 Glacier Deep Archive. S3 Standard is suitable for frequently accessed data requiring high availability and low latency, while Intelligent-Tiering automatically moves objects between tiers based on access patterns to optimize costs. Standard-IA and One Zone-IA are designed for infrequently accessed data with lower storage costs, and Glacier storage classes are used for archival workloads and long-term backups requiring minimal cost. S3 buckets are globally unique and can be configured with policies, lifecycle rules, access controls, encryption, logging, and replication settings. Bucket policies and IAM policies allow fine-grained access control for users, applications, and AWS services. S3 supports both server-side encryption and client-side encryption to protect sensitive data at rest and in transit. Encryption can be managed using Amazon S3 managed keys, AWS Key Management Service keys, or customer-provided keys. S3 Versioning enables multiple versions of the same object to be stored, helping protect against accidental deletion and overwriting. Lifecycle management policies can automatically transition objects to lower-cost storage classes or delete them after a specified retention period, improving storage efficiency and reducing operational overhead. S3 also supports cross-region replication and same-region replication for disaster recovery, compliance, and data redundancy requirements. Static website hosting is another popular feature of S3, allowing developers to host HTML, CSS, JavaScript, images, and other frontend assets directly from S3 buckets without managing traditional web servers. S3 integrates seamlessly with services such as Amazon CloudFront for low-latency global content delivery, AWS Lambda for event-driven automation, and Amazon Athena for querying data directly from S3 using SQL. Event notifications in S3 can trigger workflows when files are uploaded, deleted, or modified, enabling automation pipelines for image processing, log analysis, and serverless applications. Multipart upload functionality improves upload efficiency for large files by splitting them into smaller parts that can be uploaded independently and in parallel. S3 Transfer Acceleration uses optimized network paths and edge locations to improve upload speeds for geographically distributed users. S3 Object Lock supports write-once-read-many functionality to prevent data deletion or modification for compliance and regulatory requirements. S3 Access Points simplify managing access for shared datasets across applications and teams. Storage Lens provides visibility into storage usage, activity trends, and optimization recommendations across the organization. S3 Select enables retrieving only specific data from objects rather than downloading entire files, improving query performance and reducing costs. Amazon S3 is commonly used for backup and recovery solutions because of its durability, scalability, lifecycle management, and integration with backup tools. Data lakes built on S3 allow organizations to centralize structured, semi-structured, and unstructured data for analytics, machine learning, and business intelligence workloads. Media companies use S3 to store videos, images, and streaming content, while enterprises use it for document management, compliance storage, and application asset storage. S3 also supports hosting software packages, logs, configuration files, and IoT-generated data at massive scale. Monitoring and auditing capabilities are provided through integration with Amazon CloudWatch and AWS CloudTrail, enabling administrators to track bucket access, storage metrics, and operational activity. S3 Block Public Access helps organizations prevent accidental public exposure of sensitive data by centrally controlling bucket-level public permissions. S3 is highly available and designed to support mission-critical applications with strong consistency for read and write operations. Organizations choose Amazon S3 because it eliminates infrastructure management complexity, reduces operational costs, supports global scalability, integrates deeply with the AWS ecosystem, and provides secure, durable, and highly flexible cloud storage for nearly every type of application and workload.
"""

aws_ec2="""
Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud, commonly known as Amazon EC2, is one of the most widely used compute services provided by Amazon Web Services that allows users to create and manage virtual servers in the cloud with flexibility, scalability, and reliability. EC2 enables businesses, developers, startups, and enterprises to launch virtual machines called instances within minutes without purchasing or maintaining physical hardware. These EC2 instances can run multiple operating systems including Linux, Ubuntu, Red Hat, Debian, SUSE, and Windows Server, making the platform highly versatile for different workloads and enterprise requirements. EC2 supports a wide variety of instance types optimized for compute-intensive, memory-intensive, storage-intensive, and GPU-based workloads. General purpose instances provide a balanced combination of CPU, memory, and networking resources, while compute optimized instances are designed for high-performance applications such as gaming servers, scientific modeling, batch processing, and high-frequency trading systems. Memory optimized instances are suitable for large in-memory databases, analytics engines, and caching applications, whereas storage optimized instances provide high input/output performance for data warehousing and distributed file systems. GPU-enabled EC2 instances support machine learning training, artificial intelligence workloads, rendering, video encoding, and deep learning applications. EC2 instances can be launched using Amazon Machine Images, commonly called AMIs, which contain preconfigured operating systems, software packages, libraries, and application stacks. Users can create custom AMIs to standardize deployments across environments and simplify infrastructure management. EC2 offers flexible purchasing models including On-Demand Instances, Reserved Instances, Spot Instances, and Savings Plans, helping organizations optimize infrastructure costs according to workload patterns and budget requirements. On-Demand Instances provide flexibility without long-term commitments, Reserved Instances offer significant discounts for predictable workloads, and Spot Instances utilize unused AWS capacity at reduced pricing for fault-tolerant applications. EC2 Auto Scaling automatically increases or decreases the number of running instances based on demand, ensuring applications remain highly available during traffic spikes while minimizing costs during low-usage periods. Elastic Load Balancing distributes incoming traffic across multiple EC2 instances to improve fault tolerance, availability, and application performance. Security in EC2 is managed using Security Groups, Network ACLs, IAM roles, and key pairs for secure SSH or RDP access. Security Groups act as virtual firewalls that control inbound and outbound traffic at the instance level, while IAM roles allow secure access to AWS resources without embedding credentials in applications. EC2 instances are commonly deployed inside Amazon VPC environments to isolate resources and control network communication securely. Monitoring and observability are provided through Amazon CloudWatch, which tracks CPU utilization, memory usage, network traffic, and application logs for performance optimization and troubleshooting. EC2 instances support multiple networking configurations, Elastic IP addresses, placement groups, dedicated hosts, and enhanced networking capabilities for advanced enterprise workloads. Applications running on EC2 can scale globally using AWS Regions and Availability Zones, ensuring low latency and high disaster recovery capability. EC2 integrates seamlessly with databases, storage services, serverless platforms, analytics tools, and machine learning services across the AWS ecosystem. One of the most important storage components associated with EC2 is Amazon EBS, which stands for Amazon Elastic Block Store. EBS provides persistent block-level storage volumes that can be attached to EC2 instances similarly to physical hard drives in traditional servers. EBS volumes are designed for high durability, availability, and performance, making them ideal for operating systems, databases, enterprise applications, and transactional workloads. Unlike instance store volumes, EBS volumes retain data even after an EC2 instance is stopped or terminated if configured appropriately. EBS supports multiple volume types optimized for different workloads, including General Purpose SSD volumes, Provisioned IOPS SSD volumes, Throughput Optimized HDD volumes, and Cold HDD volumes. General Purpose SSD volumes provide a balance between price and performance and are widely used for boot volumes, web servers, and development environments. Provisioned IOPS SSD volumes are designed for mission-critical applications requiring consistent low latency and high throughput, such as relational databases and enterprise ERP systems. Throughput Optimized HDD volumes are suitable for large sequential workloads including big data processing, log analysis, and streaming applications, while Cold HDD volumes are designed for infrequently accessed data requiring low-cost storage. EBS volumes can be resized dynamically without downtime, allowing administrators to increase storage capacity or performance as application requirements grow. EBS snapshots provide incremental backups stored in Amazon S3, enabling disaster recovery, cloning, migration, and data protection strategies. Snapshots can be automated using lifecycle policies and integrated with backup solutions to ensure compliance and business continuity. EBS encryption uses AWS Key Management Service to protect sensitive data at rest and in transit, ensuring regulatory and security compliance for enterprise workloads. Multi-Attach functionality allows specific EBS volumes to be attached to multiple EC2 instances simultaneously for clustered applications requiring shared storage. EBS integrates with Auto Scaling groups, container platforms, Kubernetes clusters, and database engines for scalable cloud architectures. Performance metrics such as IOPS, throughput, queue length, and latency can be monitored through CloudWatch to optimize storage efficiency and troubleshoot bottlenecks. EBS volumes are replicated automatically within an Availability Zone to protect against hardware failures and ensure data durability. Combining EC2 and EBS provides a flexible and powerful infrastructure solution where EC2 delivers scalable compute resources and EBS provides reliable persistent storage for applications, operating systems, and databases. Organizations across industries use EC2 and EBS for hosting websites, enterprise applications, APIs, machine learning models, analytics pipelines, DevOps environments, backup systems, and large-scale distributed systems because of their scalability, cost efficiency, integration capabilities, security, and operational simplicity.
"""

result = chain.invoke({'text1':aws_s3,'text2':aws_ec2})
print(result)

chain.get_graph().print_ascii()